    {
      "id": "eeaed6e9_9686f2dd",
      "file_path": "cps-ri/src/main/java/org/onap/cps/spi/impl/CpsDataPersistenceServiceImpl.java",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 397,
      "message": "Hi Renu, 'unique key' stored in DB only apply to 'list' elements normal yang 'container' elements do not have unique keys and dont have the [@key=value] in their xpath",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6639,
        "name": "Toine Siebelink",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "toine.siebelink@est.tech",
        "username": "ToineSiebelink"
      },
      "updated": "2021-10-22 10:44:25.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "dbe2746a_647a5bc9",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "46cfecb6_ecb117a4",
      "file_path": "cps-ri/src/main/java/org/onap/cps/spi/impl/CpsDataPersistenceServiceImpl.java",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 397,
      "message": "I understand what you mean now Renu! If we were to do a search for a path such as /categories[@code=1]/books/book[@title='Dune' and @price=5] where it doesn't have to specifically be part of a list.\n\nBut within CPS when we define xpath, this means that it is an 'absolute' path, with no extra conditions. Which is currently only what this api will accept. For paths with conditions, we define the parameter as cps-path",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 7744,
        "name": "Dylan Byrne",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "dylan.byrne@est.tech",
        "username": "DylanB95EST"
      },
      "updated": "2021-10-22 10:44:52.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "dbe2746a_647a5bc9",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "359221a1_f8087fb3",
      "file_path": "cps-ri/src/main/java/org/onap/cps/spi/impl/CpsDataPersistenceServiceImpl.java",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 397,
      "message": "I thought that we are also keeping the identifier in the xpath. Sorry for the confusion.\n\nIf this is the case I think we can still delete any data-node by xpath which is available in our DB except logical dataNode (list-node). And, we should not require any specific check for list-node as it does not exist in our DB. \n\nFor example, list node is 'categories' which does not exist in our DB.\nand list-node-element is a datanode 'categories[@code=1]' which we should be able to support with existing logic.\n\nBut, if we do not find any fragment by xpath, then the issue can be \n1. wrong xpath or \n2. trying to delete list-node. \nIn this case of list node, we can use existing cpsDataPersistenceService.deleteListDataNodes(dataspaceName, anchorName, listNodeXpath) and provide a functionality which works for all data-node type.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 7680,
        "name": "Renu Kumari",
        "display_name": "Renu Kumari",
        "email": "kashi.renu@gmail.com",
        "username": "renukumari"
      },
      "updated": "2021-10-22 19:05:46.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "46cfecb6_ecb117a4",
      "unresolved": true
    },
