    {
      "id": "6b2c89c9_ebca0547",
      "file_path": "cps-service/src/main/java/org/onap/cps/api/impl/CpsDataServiceImpl.java",
      "patchset_number": 7,
      "line": 138,
      "message": "Question : Even in case of delete, do we want to send the entire data to temporal ?",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6738,
        "name": "aditya puthuparambil",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "aditya.puthuparambil@bell.ca",
        "username": "puthuparambil.aditya"
      },
      "updated": "2021-10-26 15:22:12.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "f5538983_90d74fe1",
      "file_path": "cps-ri/src/main/java/org/onap/cps/spi/impl/CpsDataPersistenceServiceImpl.java",
      "patchset_number": 7,
      "line": 396,
      "message": "I don't think we can validate the list-node like this. \n\nA node is a list node if its parent has children which starts with '<listnode>['\n\nFor example\n/bookstore/categories[@key=10] -> this xpath points to a data-node, which is a listnode element ( not a list node)\n/bookstore/categories -> is a list node (logical) and the way to find it out is to check the children of parent('/bookstore') fragment which starts with '<listnodexpath>[' ( /bookstore/categories[ ) \n\nI think as a team we need to agree on the terminology of list-node and list-node-element. I am not sure if we all mean the same thing when we say list node.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 7680,
        "name": "Renu Kumari",
        "display_name": "Renu Kumari",
        "email": "kashi.renu@gmail.com",
        "username": "renukumari"
      },
      "updated": "2021-10-26 16:07:36.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "c3105b70_3991de06",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "e66ce876_e312367f",
      "file_path": "cps-service/src/main/java/org/onap/cps/api/impl/CpsDataServiceImpl.java",
      "patchset_number": 7,
      "line": 138,
      "message": "Yes. The data for the anchor has changed hence it is required to send the updated information.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 7680,
        "name": "Renu Kumari",
        "display_name": "Renu Kumari",
        "email": "kashi.renu@gmail.com",
        "username": "renukumari"
      },
      "updated": "2021-10-26 16:07:36.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "6b2c89c9_ebca0547",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "502fddb0_482634bd",
      "file_path": "cps-ri/src/test/groovy/org/onap/cps/spi/impl/CpsDataPersistenceServiceIntegrationSpec.groovy",
      "patchset_number": 7,
      "line": 513,
      "message": "no need to test leave. test xpath of\n1) Parent should still exist\n2) sibling shoudl still exist \n3) Target is deleted\n4) child of target is deleted",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6639,
        "name": "Toine Siebelink",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "toine.siebelink@est.tech",
        "username": "ToineSiebelink"
      },
      "updated": "2021-10-26 16:41:00.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "67c4e9d4_18b9f503",
      "file_path": "cps-ri/src/main/java/org/onap/cps/spi/impl/CpsDataPersistenceServiceImpl.java",
      "patchset_number": 7,
      "line": 396,
      "message": "Hey Aditya, if you pass in an invalid xpath, a DataNodeNotFoundException will be thrown. I have added another test case to test for this.\n\nI think we may need to discuss further on the definition of a list node Renu. I was under the assumption that a list node, is any data node confined within a list.\nSuch as in the bookstore example\n/bookstore/categories[@code='02']/books[@title='The Golden Compass']\nThat both the category code and the book title are both list nodes, as they are contained within the the lists of categories and books, as per the yang  resource.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 7744,
        "name": "Dylan Byrne",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "dylan.byrne@est.tech",
        "username": "DylanB95EST"
      },
      "updated": "2021-10-27 11:41:11.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "f5538983_90d74fe1",
      "unresolved": true
    },
